*BiodivERsA Pan-European call for international research proposals on 
biodiversity and ecosystem services
*1st November 2010 -- 17th February 2011

The BiodivERsA "Pan-European call for international research proposals 
on biodiversity and ecosystem services" has been published on the 
project website: http://www.eurobiodiversa.org

Altogether, 9 countries have confirmed their participation in this 
transnational programme: France, Sweden, Austria, Germany, Spain, 
Estonia, the Netherlands, Lithuania, and Belgium (formal agreement still 
expected for Belgium). The total provisional amount of the call is more 
than 11,1 MEUR.

Scientific teams from these 9 countries will be invited to form 
transnational research consortia with a total of at least 3 different 
countries participating in the call, and to submit proposals before the 
17th of February 2011. Nevertheless, a mandatory pre-registration of the 
projects (title, summary and consortium) will have to be done before the 
5th of January 2011.

The call will address the two following themes, across all ecosystems 
and organisms:
a) Relationships between biodiversity and ecosystem services;
b) Valuation of biodiversity and ecosystem services (monetary and non 
monetary), and better incorporation of biodiversity and ecosystem 
services into society and policy.

The research proposals will be evaluated against criteria of scientific 
excellence and policy relevance. It is also expected that the European 
scope of the projects will provide a clearly identified added value to 
the research carried out.

The budget available by agency/country is now online, as well as a FAQ, 
a partner search tool and the applicant form for indicative purposes 
only, as an EPSS will be available for the application submission at a 
later stage). As national eligibility rules are applied in this 
pan-European call, the potential applicants should contact their 
National Contact Point for more information (list available on the website).

 >>> BiodivERsA is a network composed of national organisations funding 
or managing research programmes on biodiversity across Europe. The 
objectives of this ERA-Net are to promote the cooperation between 
funding agencies in the field of biodiversity research and to coordinate 
research programmes at strategic and management levels to eventually 
develop and implement joint activities.
See: http://www.eurobiodiversa.org <http://www.eurobiodiversa.org/>

