                    <font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="3"><br>
                      <b>&#8216;Internet of Things&#8217; will grow to 16 billion
                        connectable consumer devices by 2020, says
                        Analysys Mason<br>
                      </b>LONDON, UK, 29 October, 2010 &#8211; The consumer
                      &#8216;Internet of Things&#8217; (IOT) will grow to encompass
                      almost 16 billion connectable devices worldwide by
                      2020, according to the recent report, <a
href="http://mediatlasei.prnewswire.com/mediatlasei/Url.aspx?522895x194031x-405673">Internet
                        3.0: the Internet of Things</a>, from global
                      telecoms, media and IT adviser Analysys Mason (<a
href="http://mediatlasei.prnewswire.com/mediatlasei/Url.aspx?522895x194030x-213904">www.analsysymason.com</a>).<br>
                      &#8220;16 billion connectable consumer devices by 2020
                      may actually be a conservative estimate. Taking
                      into account the uncertainties inherent in
                      forecasting new technologies 10 years out, we
                      believe that a realistic maximum number of devices
                      may be 44 billion, and 6 billion a realistic
                      minimum,&#8221; said Jim Morrish, Principal Analyst at
                      Analysys Mason and author of the report. &#8220;That&#8217;s a
                      worldwide average of between 0.8 and 5.8 devices
                      for each person alive in 2020.&#8221;<br>
                      The roots of the emerging IOT market lie in
                      industrial machine-to-machine (M2M) systems. As
                      the prices of M2M communications equipment have
                      fallen, manufacturers have installed the
                      technology in an increasing amount of consumer
                      energy meters (known as &#8216;smart meters&#8217;), and have
                      started to install it in a range of household
                      equipment, cars and security systems.<br>
                      An individual consumer&#8217;s window into the IOT is
                      likely to take the form of a smartphone handset.
                      Behind that handset will sit aggregation and
                      filtering functions, management and control
                      functions, and the actual devices that constitute
                      the consumer IOT. research programme.<br>
                      &#8220;The most direct potential consequence of the IOT
                      is the generation of huge quantities of data. In a
                      hypothetical IOT environment, every physical
                      object (and many virtual objects) may have a
                      virtual twin in &#8216;the cloud&#8217;, which could be
                      generating regular updates,&#8221; said Morrish, who
                      also leads Analysys Mason&#8217;s <a
href="http://mediatlasei.prnewswire.com/mediatlasei/Url.aspx?522895x194029x-22137">Mobile
                        Content and Applications</a><br>
                      For further details on the report, Internet 3.0:
                      the Internet of Things, please visit: <a
href="http://mediatlasei.prnewswire.com/mediatlasei/Url.aspx?522895x194028x-547295">http://www.analysysmason.com/Research/Content/Reports/<br>
                        RRY04_Internet_of_Things_Oct2010/</a><br>
                      Link to press release: <a
href="http://www.analysysmason.com/About-Us/News/Press-releases/Internet-of-Things-will-grow-to-16-billion-connectable-consumer-devices-by-2020-says-Analysys-Mason/">http://www.analysysmason.com/About-Us/News/<br>
Press-releases/Internet-of-Things-will-grow-to-16-billion-connectable-<br>
                        consumer-devices-by-2020-says-Analysys-Mason/</a><br>
                      For all press enquiries, please contact Gina
                      Ghensi or Kate Brown at <a
                        href="mailto:press@analysysmason.com">press@analysysmason.com</a><br>
                      <br>
                      &gt;&gt;&gt; About Analysys Mason
                      (<a class="moz-txt-link-abbreviated" href="http://www.analysysmason.com">www.analysysmason.com</a>)<br>
                      Analysys Mason delivers strategy advice,
                      operations support, and market intelligence
                      worldwide to leading commercial and public-sector
                      organisations in telecoms, IT, and media. Analysys
                      Mason consistently delivers significant and
                      sustainable business benefits. We are respected
                      worldwide for the exceptional quality of our work,
                      our independence and the flexibility of our teams
                      in responding to client needs. The company has
                      over 250 staff in 12 offices worldwide. Our
                      headquarters are in London and we have a presence
                      in Cambridge, Dubai, Dublin, Edinburgh, Madrid,
                      Manchester, Milan, New Delhi, Paris, Singapore and
                      Washington DC.<br>
                      <br>
                      Contact: Gina GHENSI / Kate BROWN<br>
                      Email: press(a)analysysmason.com<br>
